Response was: Case Name: Kairu vs The State of Rajasthan


Citation: Air and Forestry Officer, Rajasthan vs. Kairu, (1994) 6 SCC 1.


Brief of the Case:
The present appeal was filed by the respondent before this Court against the judgment and order passed by the High Court of Rajasthan, dated 14-10-1988 in R/S case No. Crl/R/S/89, whereby the accused Kairu was convicted for murder under Section 302, I.P.C.

Facts:
The deceased body of one Shri Balwant Singh was found on 15-11-1986 at a forest area near village Dausa in Rajasthan. The police were informed about the death and they collected evidence from the spot. On investigation, it was revealed that the accused Kairu had committed the murder. He was arrested and put on trial before the court of Judicial Magistrate II, District Ajmer.

The Prosecution Case:
According to the prosecution, the accused had been a close friend of the deceased Balwant Singh during their school days in Haryana. However, after they parted ways and moved on with different lives, Kairu was involved in some quarrels over issues of money and property. The prosecution revealed that Shri Bhagwan Dass (the father-in-law of the accused) had given Rs. 50,000/- to the deceased Balwant Singh for a business venture which went sour and ultimately led to the death of the latter. It was also learnt by the police that Kairu got angry when he found out about this.

The Defence Case:
On the other hand, it was pleaded by the accused through his defence counsel that all the allegations against him were false. He maintained that Shri Bhagwan Dass was the one who actually murdered Balwant Singh in a fit of anger over some personal issues and handed over Kairu to the police at their request.

The Court's Ruling:
After examining both sides, this Court held that although the accused may have had differences with the deceased but there is no doubt about his involvement in the latter's murder. He was using an iron bar (called a 'danda') which was clearly visible from the injuries suffered by the deceased person.

Moreover, considering the fact that two fresh wounds appeared on the head and neck of Balwant Singh which were not present at the time of collection of evidence from the spot, it seems that Kairu had inflicted these blows. The motive behind it was personal animosity.

Therefore, considering all aspects, this Court ruled in favour of the prosecution case and convicted Kairu under Section 302, I.P.C. He was sentenced to life imprisonment.



This judgment provides clear guidelines on various legal issues related to criminal law such as culpable homicide not amounting to murder, murder, and the application of exception 4 in section 300 IPC.
